description:
The task is simple, create a sorting algorithm using the following 

`Nat` type
```rust
struct Z {}
struct S<N>(N);

trait Nat {
    const VAL: usize;
}

impl Nat for Z {
    const VAL: usize = 0;
}

impl<N: Nat> Nat for S<N> {
    const VAL: usize = N::VAL + 1;
}
```

`List` type
```rust
trait List {
    type ListT;
    const VAL: Self::ListT;
}

impl List for Nil {
    type ListT = ();
    const VAL: Self::ListT = ();
}

impl<X: Nat, XS: List<ListT = XST>, XST> List for Cons<X, XS> {
    type ListT = (usize, XST);
    const VAL: (usize, XST) = (X::VAL, XS::VAL);
}
```
--------

Note that whichever types you make must follow the following conventions. `Type::Value` for associated types you assigned as outputs, and `Type::VAL` for the const generics you use to convert type-level values into term-level.

for `Nat`, `Nat::VAL` is a transformation to `usize`
```rust
<S<S<Z>>>::VAL == 2 
<Z>::VAL == 0
<S<Z>>::VAL == 1
```

for `List`, `List::VAL` is a transformation to a recursive tuple.
```rust
type One = S<Z>;
type Two = S<S<Z>>;
type Three = S<S<S<Z>>>;

...

<Nil>::VAL == ()
<Cons<Two, Cons<Three, Cons<One, Nil>>>>::VAL == (2, (3, (1, ())))
```

For convenience you can use the following macro
```rust
macro_rules! list {
    () => (Nil);
    ( $x:ty ) => (Cons<$x, Nil>);
    ( $x:ty, $($xs:ty),+) => (Cons<$x, list!($($xs),+)>);
}
```
to more easily create lists

`list![One,Two]` == `Cons<One, Cons<Two, Nil>>`

-----

About Peano numbers and Cons-lists:

https://brilliant.org/wiki/peano-axioms/
https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Cons
